  {
    "page": 13,
    "block_id": "page_013:block_051",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "4.3 RQ1. Effectiveness Evaluation We select three representative state-of-the-art methods for identifying vulnerable versions in the Java ecosystem as our baselines: V-SZZ [ 9 ], which is based on commit tracing; VERJava [ 42 ], which leverages code similarity; and LLM4SZZ [ 43 ], which utilizes LLMs for vulnerability versions identification. V-SZZ traces all deleted lines in a fix commit back to their origin using git blame , treating them as vulnerability-inducing lines. To improve the accuracy of locating vulnerability-inducing commits (VICs), it also uses an AST-based line mapping algorithm. However, V-SZZ cannot handle cases where the fix commit contains no deleted lines, and the AST-based line mapping is not always accurate. VERJava addresses this limitation by supporting fix commits without deleted lines. It computes vulnerable versions at both the function level and the entire patch level, and then synthesizes the results to determine the final set of vulnerable versions. Since VERJava requires comparing every version, the computational cost is very high. As a result, the authors evaluated only a subset of versions. In contrast, to ensure the accuracy of our evaluation, we evaluate all versions of each project. For example, the VERJava study only assessed 13 versions of the Liferay Portal project, while we evaluated all 233 versions. LLM4SZZ employs rank-based identification and context-enhanced identification to handle different types of fixing commits. Table 2 and 3 present the results of CaVulner and baselines in identifying vulnerable versions in the CVE level and version level, respectively. Both LLM4SZZ and CaVulner use DeepSeek V3 as the large language model. According to the evaluation metrics, the criteria for CVE level statistics are particularly strict: if even a single predicted vulnerable version does not match the ground truth, the result cannot be counted as true. As a result, the accuracy at the CVE level is generally lower than precision and recall at the version level. Despite the stringent requirements for CVE-level accuracy, Table 2 reveals that CaVulner achieves the highest overall accuracy of 73.30%, outperforming LLM4SZZ (33.52%), V - SZZ (37.50%) and VERJava (20.45%). These results highlight the effectiveness of CaVulner in accurately identifying complete vulnerable version sets for each CVE. We examined the 47 failure cases where CaVulner failed, aiming to clarify the underlying causes of these inaccuracies. Specifically, 8 cases erroneously included non-vulnerable early versions, while 39 failed to cover the complete vulnerable range. Further analysis reveals that 27 failures stemmed from misjudged semantic equivalence, while 14 cases resulted from errors in identifying duplicated commits, and the remaining 6 were caused by incorrect initial code localization. At the version level, where predictions are evaluated at a finer granularity, Table 3 demonstrates that CaVulner again achieves superior performance across all metrics. It achieves the highest precision (98.14%), recall (83.15%), and F1-score (90.02%), indicating that it can reliably identify most vulnerable versions while introducing few false positives. In comparison, LLM4SZZ achieves a lower recall (47.20%) and F1-score (61.38%), suggesting its vulnerability identification is more conservative and incomplete. Meanwhile, VERJava, although showing slightly better recall (68.56%) than V-SZZ (51.21%), suffers from a high false positive rate, as reflected by its lower precision (63.78%) and F1-score (66.08%). Notably, CaVulner achieves 100% precision in several projects such as jackson-databind, jenkins, spring-security, and struts, indicating its ability to avoid introducing any irrelevant versions during prediction. Even in large-scale projects like jenkins and jackson-databind, which contain thousands of versions, CaVulner maintains consistently high accuracy and recall.",
